etymologies: late Middle English: via Old French from late Latin minuta, feminine (used as a noun) of minutus ‘made small’. The senses ‘period of sixty seconds’ and ‘sixtieth of a degree’ derive from medieval Latin pars minuta prima ‘first minute part’

definitions: a period of time equal to sixty seconds or a sixtieth of an hour

examples.text: he stood in the shower for twenty minutes
in ten minutes' time he could be on his way

definitions: the distance covered in sixty seconds by someone driving or walking

examples.text: the hotel is situated just ten minutes from the center of the resort

shortDefinitions: distance covered in this length of time by someone driving or walking

examples.text: come and sit down for a minute

definitions: an instant or a point of time

examples.text: she had been laughing one minute and crying the next

definitions: a period of time; a while

examples.text: I hadn't been to Manhattan in a minute
it's been a minute since the pop singer has released new music

definitions: a sixtieth of a degree of angular measurement (symbol: ʹ)

examples.text: Delta Lyrae is a double star with a separation of over 10 minutes of arc

etymologies: late Middle English (in the sense ‘lesser’, with reference to a tithe or tax): from Latin minutus ‘lessened’, past participle of minuere

examples.text: a minute fraction of an inch

definitions: so small as to verge on insignificance

examples.text: he will have no more than a minute chance of exercising significant influence

shortDefinitions: so small as to be insignificant

definitions: (of an inquiry or investigation, or an account of one) taking the smallest points into consideration; precise and meticulous

examples.text: a minute examination of the islands

etymologies: late Middle English (in the singular in the sense ‘note or memorandum’): from French minute, from the notion of a rough copy in ‘small writing’ (Latin scriptura minuta) as distinct from the fair copy in book hand. The verb dates from the mid 16th century

definitions: a summarized record of the proceedings at a meeting.
an official memorandum authorizing or recommending a course of action.
record or note (the proceedings of a meeting or a specified item among such proceedings)

examples.text: the Secretary shall minute the proceedings of each meeting
